<Document>
<name>Alpine Way — Snowy Mountains</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Alpine Way — Snowy Mountains</h2><p><i>New South Wales, Australia · Khancoban to Cooma via Thredbo and Jindabyne</i></p><p><b>210 km across Australia's highest country — Mount Kosciuszko, Snowy Hydro country, alpine ash forests.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>119 km (74 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs no stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>December–April for full open road; ski season Jun–Oct (chains may be required); closures possible</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Snow/ice June–October; brumbies (feral horses) on road; wombats at dusk; fires in summer; Black Summer 2019–20 burnt much of this country</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>231</td></tr></table><hr><p>Australia's high country — Mount Kosciuszko (2,228 m) is the country's highest, but only just; the entire main range sits between 1,500 and 2,200 m, a glacial-scoured plateau of granite tors and tussock grass. The Alpine Way runs around its western and southern flanks. The Snowy Mountains Hydro-Electric Scheme (1949–74) dammed and tunneled the Snowy River through the range — the largest engineering project in Australian history, built mostly by post-war European migrants whose accents still color the towns. The 2003 and 2019–20 fires both burnt deeply through here; you'll see ghost forests and vigorous regrowth in alternation. Brumbies (feral horses) roam in numbers and are a politically charged issue — a folk symbol to some, an environmental disaster to ecologists.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Geehi</b> — Cattle-station country at the base of the western fall of the main range. Old slab huts maintained by Mountain Cattlemen — relics of the high-country grazing tradition that ended in 1969.</li><li><b>Dead Horse Gap</b> — 1,580 m. The Alpine Way's high point. Scrub of snow gums (Eucalyptus pauciflora) on either side — the species that gives the high country its silver winter character.</li><li><b>Thredbo</b> — Australia's main alpine ski village (1,365 m). The Kosciuszko chairlift runs in summer too — you can be at the summit (2,228 m) on a 13 km return walk on a steel-mesh boardwalk that protects the fragile alpine soil.</li><li><b>Jindabyne</b> — Original town drowned by Lake Jindabyne in 1967 for the hydro scheme; current town built on the new shoreline. Trout fishing capital. The Banjo Paterson statue commemorates the bush-poet of The Man from Snowy River.</li><li><b>Cooma</b> — Snowy Mountains Hydro Scheme HQ. Avenue of Flags representing the 30+ countries the post-war workforce came from. The Snowy Hydro Discovery Centre is a free museum of the project.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
